label chapter12:

    # [Scene: Refurbished Row House | Morning]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, rising piano with a subtle electronic pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low kettle whistle, distant gulls, the muffled clank of tools from the street below]
    "You wake before your alarm. For a long second you let your eyes adjust to the soft, determined light that has always felt like the harbor remembering itself. The room smells of boiled coffee and the"
    "faint, almost medicinal scent of the lab: iodine from sample jars, paper warmed by the sun, and the oil-sweet residue from Noah's quick repairs the night before. Your wristband hums a gentle confirmation — municipal approval"
    "notices, funding disbursement, a list of community representatives. Nothing flashy. Practical things, the kinds of things that make plans breathe."
    show samir_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "Morning. They cleared the language on the governance clause. It's... tight, Mira. No loopholes for unilateral buyouts."
    "You lift an eyebrow and let the corner of your mouth tilt, grateful but cautious."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "No praetorian clauses, then? Good. We need the coalition to be accountable to people, not permit holders."

    samir_hale "Exactly. We pushed for neighborhood vetting panels. And the seats — the council agreed to designate two municipal liaison seats with binding oversight. Not everything, but enough leverage."
    "You run your thumb over the printout; the fibers of the paper feel like a promise you can measure. Your heart stirs with a small, precise joy — validation for countless nights of data, community meetings, and stubborn persistence."

    menu:
        "Read the governance clause now":
            "You lean over the document, tracing the legal language with a finger. Samir watches, then points to a line you both agree needs one more comma. The small victory is quiet but exact."
        "Call Etta to share the news":
            "You lift the phone and hear Etta's greeting, thick with place-memory. Her voice swells like tidewater as she says, 'We have mouths to feed and roofs to hold. Tell me everything.' You smile because the news will sit better in her hands than on paper."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose both, in the way people always do when the work is both practical and human — legal language first, then the elder who keeps the story intact. You talk through phrasing with Samir, then"
    "walk the short block to Noah's shop to fetch the banner he's been painting for days. The wooden floorboards give a contented creak beneath your boots; salt flakes cling to your jacket sleeves."
    "Noah meets you at the door, hands scraped but steady, paint under his nails like a map of the week. He doesn't need the printouts to know what this means."
    show noah_solace at center:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_solace "You did it, Mira. They're funding the programs. Don't go soft now."

    mira_solace "When have I ever gone soft?"

    noah_solace "When you nearly cried at Etta's soup last week."
    "The laugh is an honest thing between you, shared and immediate. The harbor outside is bright; people pass with bundles and children, the ordinary, precarious life the coalition aims to protect. You tuck the banner under"
    "your arm and the weight of it — painted letters, patchwork hem — feels like a gentle anchor."
    # [Scene: Old Pier Neighborhood | Afternoon]
    hide samir_hale
    hide mira_solace
    hide noah_solace

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Acoustic guitar and hand percussion; the tempo is steady and hopeful]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, the rhythmic thud of mallets, a breeze carrying salt and the sweet tang of kelp]
    "Etta stands near the assembly, braided silver halo catching the light. She has a thermos and a wisdom-stitched patience that always makes the room quieter when she speaks. You see her look at the banner, then"
    "at you, and the lines at the corners of her eyes soften in a way that feels like benediction."
    show etta_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_maren "We did not make this alone, Mira. We stitched it with hands that have mended nets and roofs and hearts. Remember that."
    "You feel the impulse to deflect — the reflex to fold your personal stakes into the larger spool of work — but the look she gives you is disarming. It is the look of someone who recognizes the cost and the calling in equal measure."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "We couldn't have, Etta. You kept the stories straight when everything else was fraying."

    etta_maren "Stories are the map. You and Arin Voss drew the bridges."
    "Arin Voss arrives in a dusty pair of boots, sun-creased grin like always, carrying a crate of seedlings and the unmistakable energy of someone who believes that action is its own argument. He drops a bundle of reclaimed materials and crosses to you, hands smudged with soil."
    show arin_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "You look like you could use a trowel and a toast."

    mira_solace "Both, actually. And maybe a short speech when the meeting folds into the signing. Keep it short, technical, human."

    arin_voss "Short, technical, human? That's your brand now, Mira. Since when did you become the slogan?"
    "The banter washes through you; it is familiar and warming. Underneath, a deeper current: you and Arin Voss have always turned toward action together, but co-leading something formal — an institution that will outlast the heat"
    "of this moment — is a different kind of intimacy. It requires trust, scheduling, patience, and the discipline to share the spotlight."

    menu:
        "Practice a technical opener":
            "You step to a crate, voice steady. 'Data shows localized sea-level acceleration at the north berth...' Your words are crisp; listeners nod, notebooks open."
        "Start with a memory of the Old Pier":
            "You breathe and tell the story of your childhood rope swing and the storm that took your house. Faces tilt; you feel warmth, not exposure. The room leans in."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose the memory — not because numbers don't matter, but because this coalition will live or die on the stories that make people care. Your voice wavers once, then finds the line. The room responds with a collective, held rhythm: understanding, grief, resolve."

    etta_maren "True work is the kind that holds people and places. Today you hold both."
    "Hands move to sign attendance sheets and to register neighborhood representatives. A municipal liaison from the Mayor's office arrives, modest and earnest, with Samir walking them through the oversight structure. There is a practical choreography to"
    "the day: training on maintaining vegetated berms, a rota for community watch during storms, and a schedule for monthly open forums at the Old Pier. Each ritual is small but formal enough to be durable."
    "Arin Voss pulls you aside for a heartbeat, eyes bright with that fierce, impatient joy he always has when something is possible."

    arin_voss "Can you believe it? We actually have a steering committee. Real seats. Not just promises."

    mira_solace "It's steady. It's not everything, but it's enough to keep us honest."
    "You let the reserve you've always worn loosen in the way of someone who has earned the right to hope out loud. The sun hangs at a forgiving angle; you feel, for the first time in a long while, the harbor answering back."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Garden | Dusk]
    hide etta_maren
    hide mira_solace
    hide arin_voss

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Lush strings bloom; a chorus of soft voices rises under the melody]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The low murmur of a crowd, the clink of glasses, a distant gull calling as the tide turns]
    "The launch ceremony is small and precise, a gathering of people with hands that fix things and people with faces that keep watch. Samir gives a crisp summary of the municipal commitments — funding releases, municipal"
    "oversight seats, a matching program for small business resilience. The words land like measured bricks."
    show samir_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "We have guarantees for two years of program funding, municipal liaisons with voting oversight, and a legal anchor that prevents unilateral displacement projects within coalition zones."
    "You feel the weight of the announcements, but the lightness of consequence — these are practical steps that will let people plan. People begin to clap, some quietly, some with the rough enthusiasm of those who have waited to be heard."
    "Liora Kade arrives at the edge of the crowd. She moves with that same precise poise she has always had: trench coat, careful smile. The expression she offers you is complex — a practiced empathy braided"
    "with a strategist's calculation. You can read elements of concession in the lines around her mouth, and elements of reservation in the tightness of her shoulders. It feels honest in its ambiguity, and you accept that"
    "it is the shape of large compromises."
    show liora_kade at right:
        zoom 0.7

    liora_kade "No one wins plans like this alone. You made hard, necessary compromises. The city will be more resilient for it."
    show mira_solace at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "We made sure more of us stay in the places we love. That's the measure."
    "She inclines her head as if measuring the words. You don't need to know every corner of her past motives to feel that today holds more than a single person can carry. The coalition has shifted power in small, important ways."
    "Arin Voss stands beside you as Samir steps back to the microphone, and there's a hush. Etta is at your left, Noah beaming at the front as he holds the painted banner like a flag. People"
    "you taught to take water and soil samples stand with senior municipal staff; children who have planted seeds cluster at planters, fingers still dirty."

    samir_hale "By unanimous vote of the founding assembly, and with community endorsement, the Solace Coalition for Harbor Resilience appoints its interim co-directors."
    "Silence blooms into concentrated attention. You sense the hinge of the moment: formal titles, public accountability, and the scaffolding of something meant to endure. You and Arin Voss exchange a look — an unspoken inventory of what this will require."
    hide samir_hale
    show arin_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "Co-director. Sounds very official for the two of us who fix things and break things with equal enthusiasm."

    mira_solace "We'll make it official because it's a way to share responsibility and make commitments stick."
    "The crowd begins to clap: not euphoric but steady, a long, practical applause that feels like people taking hold of a rope in unison. Etta squeezes your hand; Noah lifts the banner higher. Liora Kade's eyes"
    "— complex — flick to the signed documents on the small table. A municipal liaison nods to Samir, who gives a small, private smile of relief."
    "Arin Voss reaches for the pen first, and you for the second. For a moment, everything tightens into a suspended second: the paper, the pens, the hum of the rooftop, the harbor breathing below."
    "You think of the tide charts in your notebook, of nights spent mapping where people could safely rebuild, of Etta's stories and Noah's stubbornness and Samir's quiet corrections. You think of the years ahead — the"
    "meetings, the negotiations, the rainy nights and the green rooftops — and of the life you might build with someone who also knows how to keep promises."
    "You and Arin Voss lean in together; the pens hover."
    hide liora_kade
    hide mira_solace
    hide arin_voss

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A warm, ascending chord held at full]
    "You look at Arin Voss. He looks at you. For a heartbeat the world narrows to breath and the small, chosen courage of vows."
    show mira_solace at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "This is not the end of work. It is the beginning of durable labor. It is everything and nothing like the protest songs and plan drafts that brought us here. It is a promise written in ink that will be tested by rain and time. You can sign. You can step forward. You can accept a new rhythm of shared responsibility."
    "You feel steadier than you have in months — not because the stakes are less, but because they are distributed now, held in the hands of many."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The quiet intake of a crowd, as if the city itself is listening]
    "You and Arin Voss lower your pens."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells and then resolves into a gentle, hopeful cadence]
    hide mira_solace

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_5 at full_bg

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    "THE END"
